===Etymology===
From 5th century {{etyl|la}} {{term|oxymoron|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|ὀξύς||sharp|tr=oxus|lang=grc}} (English {{term|oxy-|lang=en}}, as in {{term|oxygen|lang=en}}) + {{term|μωρός||dull|tr=mōros|lang=grc}} (English {{term|moron||stupid person|lang=en}}).<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D%2374333]</ref> Literally “sharp-dull”, itself an '''oxymoron''', hence [[autological]]; compare {{term|sophomore|lit=wise fool|lang=en}}, influenced by similar analysis. The compound form *{{term||ὀξύμωρον||tr=oxumōron|lang=grc}} is not found in the extant Greek sources.<ref>OED: [http://dictionary.oed.com.ezproxy.sfpl.org/cgi/entry/50168789]</ref>

